'''''Gravitas''''' was one of the [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] [[virtue]]s,<ref name="apuzzo">{{cite journal |last=Apuzzo |first=L.J. |last2=Michael |first2=M.D.| date=August 2006 |title=Gravitas, Severitas, Veritas, Virtus |url= http://journals.lww.com/neurosurgery/Citation/2006/08000/Gravitas,_Severitas,_Veritas,_Virtus.1.aspx | language=English |journal=Neurosurgery |volume=59 |issue=2 |page=219 |doi= 10.1227/00006123-200608000-00001|access-date= 6 December 2016|quote=|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20161220213131/http://journals.lww.com/neurosurgery/Citation/2006/08000/Gravitas,_Severitas,_Veritas,_Virtus.1.aspx |archive-date=2016-12-20 |dead-url=yes }}</ref> along with ''[[pietas]]'', ''[[Dignitas (Roman concept)|dignitas]]'', and ''[[virtus]]'', that were particularly appreciated in leaders. Evidence shows that it was most likely influenced by the [[Greek language|Greek]] virtue of ''[[Arete]]''. It may be translated variously as weight, seriousness, dignity, and importance and [[connotation|connotes]] a certain substance or depth of personality. It also conveys a sense of responsibility and commitment to the task.<ref name="apuzzo" /> In the British education system, ''gravitas'' was seen as one of the pillars of the moral formation of the English gentleman during the [[Victorian era|Victorian]] and [[Edwardian era|Edwardian]] eras.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Hingley |first=Richard| year=1996 |title=The ‘legacy’ of Rome: the rise, decline, and fall of the theory of Romanization |trans-title= |url=https://lra.le.ac.uk/handle/2381/28433 |language=English |journal=Roman imperialism : post-colonial perspectives |volume= |issue=3 |page=37 |isbn=0951037765|series=Leicester Archaeology Monographs |access-date=|publisher=Webster, J.; Cooper, N. |quote=The men of the ruling upper and upper-middle classes were educated in a public school system where Classical language and literature formed basic elements of the curriculum. Greek and Roman concepts, in particular the significant Roman concept of gravitas, played a fundamental role in the formation of the character of the English gentleman (Mason 1982, 22).}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Mason |first1=Philip |last2= |first2= |date=1982 |title=The English Gentleman: The Rise and Fall of an Ideal |trans-title= |url= |access-date=|dead-url= |format= |language=English |location= |publisher= |isbn= |archive-url= |archive-date= |page=22 |subscription= |quote=}}</ref>

In the UK [[House of Commons]], the quality is known as "bottom".<ref>{{citation |pages=250,271 |title=Westminster Man: A Tribal Anthropology of the Commons People |author=[[Austin Mitchell]], Sharon Goulds |publisher=Thames Methuen |year=1982 |isbn=9780423003802}}</ref>

